Under the optimal conditions described above, the quantitative determination of TZ in the solution was successful. As shown in Fig. 7
                        a, N,P-CQDs exhibited two emission peaks at 331 nm and 481 nm. The peak at 331 nm decreased with the addition of TZ, whereas the peak at 481 nm remained unchanged (Fig. 7a). Finally, the fluorescence of N,P-CQDs was largely quenched when the TZ concentration reached 30 µmol/L. The relationship between F331/F481 and TZ concentration was determined. F331/F481 had a great linear correlation with TZ rates ranging from 0.01 to 30 µmol/L (Fig. 7b), and the linear regression equation could be conveyed as Y = 7.419–0.1332C where R2 = 0.9996 and the limit of detection (LOD) was 0.002 µmol/L, which indicated a good detection sensitivity at a low TZ concentration. The constructed fluorescent probes based on N,P-CQDs exhibited lower detection limits for TZ detection, confirming that N,P-CQDs are ideal for TZ detection. When compared with the reported methods [5–7], this method offers the advantages of high sensitivity, low detection limit, wide linear range, simplicity, and rapidity (Table 1
                        ).
